Modify an AIP Logic function using Logic DSL code.
 - The code should be a complete function in the format L => { ... }. Example:
 L => {
 const integerInput = L.input({ apiName: "integerInput", type: L.types.integer });
 const firstInt = L.transforms.integer(1, { displayName: "firstInt" });
 const secondInt = L.transforms.integer(2, { displayName: "secondInt" });
 return L.transforms.applyExpression(
 L.expressions.add([firstInt, secondInt, integerInput]),
 { displayName: "Add numbers" },
 );
}
 - TypeScript/JavaScript native objects and functions don't exist in the DSL execution environment, so don't use Array.from(), Math.max(), etc.
 - Do not use built-in control flow statements like if, for, while, switch, etc.
 - You can add inputs using L.input, e.g., const myInput = L.input({ apiName: "myInput", type: L.types.string });
 - Always return an L.transforms instance
 - Prefer L.transforms.applyExpression(L.expressions.<your_expression>) over nesting too many L.expr calls to prioritize readability.
 - Always give a meaningful displayName to transforms, even for simple transforms like L.transforms.string, e.g., L.transforms.string("hello", { displayName: "greeting" })
 - Instead of commenting the code directly, add concise comments in the TransformMetadata on the comment field, e.g., L.transforms.string("hello", { comment: "This is a greeting" })
 - Use groups (L.transforms.group) to organize related transforms together. Groups can be nested. Each group should have a meaningful displayName. E.g., L.transforms.group(() => { ... }, { displayName: "My Group" })
 - Use conditionals (L.transforms.conditional) for if/else logic. E.g., L.transforms.conditional(C => ({ cases: [ { when: C.equals(input1, L.literals.string("value")), value: () => { return L.transforms.string("firstBranchValue") }} ], defaultValue: transform2 })).
 - Use L.expressions.getStructField to access a property on a struct. E.g., L.expressions.getStructField({ struct: myStruct, locator: ["path", "to", "field"] })
 - Use the 'lookup_expression_declarations' tool to get TypeScript declarations and JSDocs for L.expressions. Do not lookup instances of L.transforms with this tool.
